<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="39">
Genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24858" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pseudomyrmex Lund" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pseudomyrmex Lund</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="39">
Ants in this predominantly Neotropical genus nest in hollow dead twigs and other preformed plant cavities. Two species occur in California: 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35737" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pseudomyrmex apache Creighton" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apache">P.apache Creighton</taxonomicName>
is widespread at middle and low elevations within the California floristic province, often nesting in branches of manzanita (
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181283" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Arctostaphylos" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName-HNS="Arctostaphylos " order="Ericales" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Arctostaphylos</taxonomicName>
), while 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:35812" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pseudomyrmex pallidus (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidus">P. pallidus (F. Smith)</taxonomicName>
is confined to southern California.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
